{{Infobox NRHP | name =Chamber of Commerce Building | nrhp_type = | image = Chamber_of_Commerce_Building_2012-09-04_15-33-36.jpg | caption = Chamber of Commerce Building, September 2012 | location= 17 Commerce St., [[Baltimore, Maryland]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|17|20|N|76|36|36|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA | built = {{Start date|1904}} | architect = Cassell, Charles E. | architecture = Renaissance | added = February 2, 1983 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 83002929<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} The '''Chamber of Commerce Building''' is a historic [[office building]] located at [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]]. It is a [[Renaissance Revival]]-style red brick building five floors in height, eleven bays long and three bays wide, and built 1904-05. It was built during the rebuilding of the financial area in Baltimore following the Great Fire of 1904 and features many [[terra cotta]] decorative elements. The rebuilt structure was designed by Baltimore architect [[Charles E. Cassell]].<ref name="mht_ihp">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-727.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Chamber of Commerce Building|date=March 1982|accessdate=2016-03-01 |author=Marc Schabb|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref> The original pre-fire building was designed by [[John Rudolph Niernsee]] in 1880 and was used by the Corn and Flour Exchange, which maintained a trading floor on the fifth level.<ref name="baltarch">{{cite book|last=Dorsey|first=John|author2=Dilts, James D.|title=A Guide to Baltimore Architecture|publisher=Tidewater Publishes|location=Centreville, Maryland|year=1981|edition=Second|pages=84–85|isbn=0-87033-272-4}}</ref>
Chamber of Commerce Building was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1983.<ref name="nris"/>
